  1. create a new variable, BSD, which is the ratio of average male to female body mass
d$BSD <- d$Body_mass_male_mean / d$Body_mass_female_mean
  1. create a new variable named sex_ratio, which is the ratio of the number of adult females to adult males in a typical group
d$sex_ratio <- d$AdultFemale / d$AdultMales
  1. create a new variable named DI (for defensibility index), which is the ratio of day range length to the diameter of the home range

diameter of homerange:

  • presume homerange is the circles area, what is the diameter?

AREA = A = pi*(r^2) . The variable pi (note, without parentheses) will return the value of as a constant built-in to R, and the function sqrt() can be used to calculate the square root ()

diameter = 2*r r = sqrt(Area/pi) = sqrt(HomeRange_km2/pi)

thus the diameter of homerange = 2r = 2(sqrt(HomeRange_km2/pi))

but remember to draw HomeRange_km2 from the dataset using d$

d$DI <- d$DayLength_km / (2 * sqrt(d$HomeRange_km2/pi))
  1. Plot the relationship between day range length and time spent moving, for these primate species overall and by family.

In the table we see that: DayLength_km = day range length (y) Move = time spent moving (x)

without any transformations:

# plot object and color points by Family
p <- ggplot(data = d, aes(x = Move, y = DayLength_km, 
    color = factor(Family))) 

# axis labels
p <- p + xlab("Time Spent Moving") + ylab("Day Range Length (km)")
# make a scatterplot, omit missing data with na.rm
p <- p + geom_point(na.rm = TRUE)
# modify legend
p <- p + theme(legend.position = "bottom", legend.title = element_blank())

p

the plot above WIHTOUT a transformation does not give us the best representation of the data, the points are too clustered in one area. so we will replot with a Log transformation

Log transformation:

# plot object and color points by Family
p <- ggplot(data = d, aes(x = log(Move), y = log(DayLength_km),
    color = factor(Family)))

# axis labels
p <- p + xlab("log(Time Spent Moving)") + ylab("log(Day Range Length (km))")
# make a scatterplot, omit missing data with na.rm
p <- p + geom_point(na.rm = TRUE)
# modify legend
p <- p + theme(legend.position = "bottom", legend.title = element_blank())

p

QUESTIONS: Do species that spend more time moving travel farther overall? - no, the scatter plot does not show a clear positive linear slope that would indicate that species that spend more time moving also travel further

How about within any particular primate family? - no even within each family there is not a clear trend correlating more time moving to farther distance traveled

Should you transform either of these variables? - yes, as shown above, the log transformation of x and y gives us a much more normal data distribution

QUESTIONS: Do species that live in larger groups travel farther overall? - certain families do show this trend, with a positive linear slope in their data; however, not all of the groups show this so we cannot assume that this is an overall trend

How about within any particular primate family? - some families, such as Cercopithecidae, Hominidae, and Lorisidae do suggest that when they live in larger groups, they also travel farther; other groups, like Lemuridae, show no significant correlation between the two variables

Should you transform either of these variables? - Once again the log transformation of both variables allows us to best visualize the data

  1. Create a new variable named diet_strategy that is frugivore if fruits make up >50% of the diet, folivore if leaves make up >50% of the diet, and omnnivore if neither of these is true. Then, do boxplots of group size for species with different dietary strategies.

1st- create new variable diet_strategy > use mutate()

2nd- use conditional expression > in this case case_when() because we are dealing with multiple if statements

  • here Im using the pipe operator to join the two functions
# modify dataset d
# mutate()- adds column titled 'diet_strategy'
d <- d %>%
  mutate(diet_strategy = case_when(
    Fruit > 50 ~ "frugivore",
    Leaves > 50 ~ "folivore",
    TRUE ~ "omnivore" #basically applies to all data that doesn't fit into the original 2 criteria/cases mentioned
  )
  )

Now time to make the BOXPLOTS for this data (x= species with same diet strategy, y= group size):

p <- ggplot(data = d, aes(x = diet_strategy, y = log(MeanGroupSize)))
p <- p + geom_boxplot(na.rm = TRUE) #plot boxplot and omit missing data
p <- p + theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90))
p <- p + ylab("log(Mean Group Size)")
p <- p + xlab("Diet Strategy")
p

QUESTIONS: Do frugivores live in larger groups than folivores? - no, while the median of mean group sizes for frugivores is slightly higher than that of folivores, the interquartile ranges of both overlap so much that this is not a significant difference

  1. In one line of code, using {dplyr} verbs and the forward pipe (%>%) operator, do the following:
  1. Add a variable, Binomial to the data frame d, which is a concatenation of the Genus and Species

  • same process as before with mutate()

    1. Trim the data frame to only include the variables Binomial, Family, Brain_size_species_mean, and Body_mass_male_mean

  • use select() from dplyr

    1. Group these variables by Family

  • use group_by() from dplyr

    1. Calculate the average value for Brain_size_species_mean and Body_mass_male_mean per Family (remember, you may need to specify na.rm = TRUE)

  • use summarize()

    1. arrange by increasing average brain size

  • use arrange()

# the isntructions said to make these changes to dataset d, but I didn't want to alter the original changes to the dataset made from the previous problems, so I created the new dataset, d2

# if you want to directly change d, then change d2 to d below
d2 <- d %>%
  # first let's add/mutate in the new variable Binomial
  mutate(Binomial = paste(Genus, Species, sep = " ")) %>%
  # select only the variables we want to still include (listed above)
  select(Binomial, Family, Brain_Size_Species_Mean, Body_mass_male_mean) %>%
  
  # NOTE!! - if you want "Binomial" to be represented in the dataset then stop at line 224 and remove the pipe operator!
  
  # group by Family from dataset d
  group_by(Family) %>%
  #calculate averages for brain size and male body mass
  summarize(avgBrainSize = mean(Brain_Size_Species_Mean, na.rm = TRUE),
    avgMale_BodyMass = mean(Body_mass_male_mean, na.rm = TRUE)) %>%
  #arrange by increasing average brain size
  arrange(avgBrainSize)
